messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /invoices/{id}

All methods acceptable:
- false

Methods acceptable (based on code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation:
- The route prefix is registered in index.js with app.use('/invoices', invoiceRoutes). (index.js)
- In routes/invoices.js the route that maps to getInvoice is router.get('/:id', getInvoice). Combining the prefix and route yields /invoices/{id} with id as a path parameter. (routes/invoices.js)
- The controller getInvoice (controllers/invoices.js) reads req.params.id and uses InvoiceModel.findById(id), confirming this is a GET handler for the {id} path. (controllers/invoices.js)
- The same path pattern ('/:id') is also used for router.patch('/:id', updateInvoice) and router.delete('/:id', deleteInvoice), so PATCH and DELETE are accepted for /invoices/{id}. (routes/invoices.js)
- There is no router.post('/:id') or router.put('/:id'), nor any router.all(...) or app.all(...) for this path, so POST and PUT are not accepted according to the source code. HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are not explicitly registered in the code, so they are marked false per the instruction to base decisions on the code (not on framework implicit behavior).
